features: Interactive toy for toddlers: This montessori toy car set includes a police car, fire engine, ambulance, ice cream cart, school bus, and regular bus, providing endless opportunities for imaginative play

Learning manipulatives for preschoolers: Our learning locks help toddlers 1-3 recognize numbers and improve their fine motor skills. Counting dots on the cars and finding the right key to unlock the locks encourages numeracy and problem-solving.

Safe and non-toxic: Made with BPA-free plastic and no sharp edges, these toys are safe for baby 6-12 12-18 months to play with and explore. The bright colors and fun designs also enhance sensory stimulation and make them a great toddler travel toy.
Perfect gift for infants: Packaged in attractive packaging, this toy set makes a great gift for birthdays, Christmas, Easter, and more. Suitable for boys and girls ages 1 2 3 one two three years old

Educational toddler toys: Featuring double-sided printing with dots and words from 1 to 6, these toys provide a foundation for early learning and help children progress from simple to more complex concepts. They're an excellent choice for parents looking for educational toys that are also fun and engaging.

manufacturerProductDescription.media_text: Baby Sensory Board kids' play motor vehicles and Montessori Number Learning Locks 2IN 1building counting skills! Our learning locks help kids recognize numbers as well as fine motor coordination
Gifts for toddlers Nice packaged Great for gifting: suitable gift for any occasion including baby showers, birthdays, Christmas, Easter and more

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 10, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Fun learning toy
reviews.reviewText: Fun toy with multiple learning features. Got for an 18 month old and it took a bit for her to learn to unlock them, so a good toy to grow with your child.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 27, 2023
reviews.reviewText: Perfect to keep my 19mo busy! The keys are definitely a breakable plastic and I wish the numbers on the locks were actual numbers and not just spelled out (6 vs six). I like that the locks have wheels on them to roll as little cars.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 9, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Cute and Easy to Use!
reviews.reviewText: Got these for 3yo’s birthday, and they were a hit! She was super engaged with them and used them right away.The keys are all different and match with the car lock with the same number.The cars are all different kinds of vehicles, too which is super fun. Police car, fire truck, taxi, ice cream truck, etc. The wheels on them work, too, so they can be used just as toy cars!The locks are easy to open and close, too. So far, none of them have stuck or anything.They’re good sized, too. We can actually put the locks on different things to make it more engaging.Very great for counting, number recognition, and reading the spelling of the numbers. Good problem solving toy.All in all, these are super cute and very fun. Might get these again as a gift for my friends’ kids.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 3, 2024
reviews.reviewText: My two year old is obsessed with keys so when I gave him these he was thrilled!! Great for travel, keeps him busy trying to match keys to the locks.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 28, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 3.0 out of 5 stars A little flimsy.
reviews.reviewText: Helps with matching writing and numbers. The keys themselves are flimsy. I am worried one will break, but none have broken yet. The ring the keys come on is worthless. It doesn't stay closed so if you don't want little plastic keys everywhere make sure you have another child safe ring to put them on.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 28, 2022
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Toddler LOVES this
reviews.reviewText: 3yo on the spectrum loves counting and repetitive tasks...I mean...it clicks open, and they are cars, and he can count the dots and read the numbers and find the numbers on the key ring, and it's a hit with him. It's a calming sort of task that I won't let him do all day, but it is good for manual dexterity too. I wish I had found these when he needed more manual dexterity training, it might have been more useful than just entertaining, they're cool. My one concern is the paint seems likely to chip...been keeping them from baby because I don't want her chewing on them because of the paint and wheels. I don't think I would recommend for any child who chews on stuff in all honesty, imo.
